NAME
    execle(3)    	- execute a file as a process

SYNOPSIS
    execle( name, arg0, arg1, ..., argn, 0, envp )
      char *name, *arg0, *arg1, ..., *argn, *envp[];

    execl( name, arg0, arg1, ..., argn, 0 )
      char *name, *arg0, *arg1, ..., *argn;

    execv( name, argv )
      char *name, *argv[];

    execn( name )
      char *name;

DESCRIPTION
    These calls are simpler calls to execve(2). The first two
    routines allow the "argv" vector to be given as a list
    of strings, terminated by a zero. The execl(3) and execv(3)
    routines are like execle(3) and execve(2) respectively, except 
    that no user environment is passed.

    For the special case of no argument list and no environment
    the execn(3) call is useful.

SEE ALSO
    execve(2), environ(4)

BUGS
    The calls execl() and execv() don't pass the environment, I think
    they should.
